Text: Scoping is hard.
And it's not just about scoping the project.
There are also your own expectations, each team member's expectations to scope, down or out.
And then there are clashing expectations as well.
Susu made it clear from the beginning that she wants to deliver something that works.
Gogo and Bibi seem quite confident that a full-blown desktop application will work.
They also know that they don't want to travel down Excel-land.
What about me?
I don't know, maybe a bit of both, so I could only imagine.
Let's just say that we did finish the app and managed to port most of Millair's workflow there.
That would be great, wouldn't it?
Everyone would upscale their tech skills, the client is happy.
Everything would automatically update, all quirky rules are handled, and reports are generated easily.
But what if something went wrong along the way?
It's risky.
Trying to abstract away all the complicated rules through building a full-blown app from the ground up.
And the system is by no means straight-forward.
What if certain policy changes necessitate a schema change?
What if certain factors are added or removed from the salary formula?.
Although we did say we will focus on just the on-call-hour functionality, Milair would still have to go back to her excel files again to transfer those new hours onto her reports.
It would still be a partial system.
And in a sense that's one more system for her to maintain and keep track of.
Maybe we should learn from Excel before striking out on our own to make something that is "all-or-nothing".
And to be fair to Excel, if all records are grouped into one file, one can use filter out those that need to be updated.
There are after all just over 300 doctors, meaning it's just about 300 rows.
Besides, there are already basic and even somewhat complex filtering mechanisms built into Excel.
If she wants to update the hours of a team, she just needs to filter out records of team A, and anniversary date would be easy as well.
Just filter out records with date equal to X.
Maybe data normalization is not really necessary.
Plus, everything is visible, editable, and you can easily duplicate records as backup from within Excel.
Putting everything into a database and then presenting it out again seems a waste of time and effort.
Besides, the user, who's not technical-savvy loses direct control over the actual data itself.
Finally, someone needs to do the data entry as well.

When I raised this issue, my teammates just said it's okay as long as we know the columns, that Milair can probably do it herself or hire someone else to spend a few hours on it, but also means we need to build a data-entry functionality as well.
But doesn't Excel already provide that?
Personally I feel like the problem is not with Excel, but with Milair's wanting a feature that Excel doesn't really have.

And as a team I feel like we're overlooking the strengths and benefits that Excel has already provided for Millair:  visibility, ease of CRUD operations especially for non-tech users, and intuitive UI.
I personally think the reason why she keeps each doctor's record in one Excel file is for her to be able to generate a report off that file.

So maybe if build something that allows her to edit all records in bulk or in team, and still generate an individual report for one person in a nice-looking template, that may just be a good compromise.
This way, all the updates could still be conveniently done on Excel, using Excel functionalities and a few formulas or tricks for Milair as part of our user manual.
She probably only has a dozen of updates to do every day, and it's probably okay just doing it within one spreadsheet.
But even if this benefits the client, would it benefit my teammates?
We're all reluctant.
We're not doing this to learn and get good at Excel.
Scoping is hard, especially when everyone is a stakeholder.
Maybe I'm just overthinking.
I do feel somewhat frustrated.
Maybe it's because everything is so vague, and everyone is so confident about it all.
Maybe it's because I feel like we haven't really talked about what really makes a difference for our client.
Maybe because I feel so ridiculous for stressing out so much over what it's after all a student project.
So what am I planning to do next week?
I'll try to communicate my concerns to my team.
We're having a meeting on Monday so hopefully my team will help me get a better sense of direction.
Perhaps the whole app is doable, I'm just being paranoid, and I will be able to continue my database unit testing journey without care and worries.
(A quick update in case you haven't read the blog before I wrote this.
We decided as a team to finish the Excel solution as something to fall back on, but still develop a full-blown application for our own learning.
Plus, judging from our conversation with Milair, the app would enable her to do a lot more beyond keeping everything updated, which Excel doesn't allow her to do. )
Overall
